# CrowdVision — Software Process Engineering Report

**Authors:** Nicolò Ghignatti · Mounir Samite · Ettore Farinelli
**Course:** Software Process Engineering · **Date:** June 2026

CrowdVision is a **digital-twin and crowd-analytics platform**. In plain terms, it takes live data
from sensors scattered around a building and shows it on an interactive 3D model, so whoever runs the
place can see — right now — how crowded a room is, how warm it is, and whether anything needs
attention. It scales from a single floor to a whole campus.

This report is not really a tour of the features. It is more the story of *how we built it*: how we
organised ourselves, the choices we made about design and architecture, and the tooling that carries
a commit all the way to a running, deployed service. We have tried to keep it high-level — whenever a
topic deserves a closer look, we point to the **exact page of the
[Developer Guide](../../dev/Developer-Guide/)** rather than repeating it here.

.box {How to read this} type:{note}
    Every section ends with a **Read more** box linking to the precise Developer-Guide page — and,
    where it helps, the exact section — that goes deeper than we do here.

---

# 1 · Introduction

CrowdVision is a **polyglot microservices system** living in a single **monorepo** — every service,
all the shared tooling, the infrastructure manifests and the documentation sit in one Git
repository. We landed on nine deployable pieces: seven backend services, two device simulators, and a
Vue single-page app for the browser.

## 1.1 Project goals

We started from a handful of goals. Each one quietly shaped both the architecture and the pipeline:

.var {headers}
   - Goal
   - How we got there

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - **Microservices that mean something**
      - We let Domain-Driven Design draw the boundaries — one bounded context per service, each owning its own database.
    - - **The right language for the job**
      - Services run on three stacks: TypeScript on Node.js, Python, and Rust. We picked per workload, not by habit.
    - - **One way to build everything**
      - A single command (`just`, on top of `mise` and `moon`) builds, tests and lints every language, sharing one cache.
    - - **Automation we can trust, with security baked in**
      - Pipelines handle build, test, lint, dependency and container scanning, static analysis, docs, image publishing and deployment.
    - - **Runs the same everywhere**
      - Every service ships as a Docker image; the system runs under Docker Compose on a laptop and on Kubernetes in production.

## 1.2 How we organised the work

Three habits carried the day-to-day:

- **Version control.** We work on **GitHub Flow**: `master` is the one protected branch, and nothing
  reaches it except through a reviewed pull request that passes the automated gate. Commit messages
  follow **Conventional Commits**, and branches follow a naming convention — both checked by a
  machine, not by trust.
- **Build & quality.** **moon** runs each project's `build` / `test` / `lint` / `audit` tasks,
  caches the results, and only re-runs what a change actually touched, so a one-line edit never
  rebuilds the whole repo. Every service brings its own tests, linting and dependency audit.
- **Release & deployment.** We don't pick version numbers — **semantic-release** reads them straight
  off the commit history. Every merge to `master` cuts a release, builds and scans the images, and
  pushes them to **GHCR**, which is exactly where production pulls from.

## 1.3 Licensing

CrowdVision is **proprietary, source-available software** — *“All rights reserved”*. The repository
is public so anyone can read the code and judge it. GitHub's terms let people view and fork it on
GitHub, but any fork stays under our licence — running it, building a product from it, redistributing
it elsewhere or selling it is off the table without our say-so.

That is a conscious middle ground. Permissive licences (MIT, Apache-2.0) would let someone fold the
code into a closed product; strong copyleft (GPL-3.0) would force every derivative to stay open. We
wanted neither — we wanted the work to be **open to inspection while staying ours to govern**.

This openness is deliberately for *now*. We like having CrowdVision in the open, where it can be read
and learned from, and we intend to keep it that way through this stage of the project. But the plan is
for CrowdVision to grow into a product, so we have reserved the right to change the terms and **make
the repository private** when that moment comes. Staying source-available today and closing the source
later is a planned step, not an afterthought.

.box {Read more} type:{tip}
    Goals and scope: [Functional Requirements](../../dev/Developer-Guide/functional-requirements/) ·
    [Non-Functional Requirements](../../dev/Developer-Guide/non-functional-requirements/) ·
    [User Stories](../../dev/Developer-Guide/user-stories/). The full terms live in the
    repository `LICENSE`.

