# 2 · Design

The system is a set of **microservices**, each one modelling a single slice of the domain and owning
its own data. We leaned on Domain-Driven Design throughout, but treated it as a **compass, not a
rulebook**: the strategic boundaries are the part we were most sure of; the tactical detail we added
only where it paid for itself.

## 2.1 The domain, and how we split it

The domain, boiled down, is *watching physical spaces in real time through a digital twin*. We sorted
the subdomains by how much they actually set the product apart — which then told us where to spend
our modelling effort:

.var {headers}
   - Subdomain (type)
   - Lives in

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - Spatial Digital Twin · *Core*
      - twin-service
    - - Telemetry Ingestion & Thresholds · *Core*
      - sensor-service
    - - Telemetry Distribution · *Core*
      - contracts-service
    - - Identity & Access · *Supporting*
      - auth-service
    - - Alerting · *Supporting*
      - notification-service
    - - Knowledge & Assistance · *Supporting*
      - agent-service
    - - Real-Time Transport · *Generic*
      - socket-service

Every core and supporting subdomain became exactly one **bounded context**, and we made that boundary
do double duty as a storage and deployment boundary too. The contexts talk to each other through the
familiar DDD patterns: the signed **identity token is the Published Language** everyone agrees on,
while the building-to-telemetry and building-to-alerting links are **Customer/Supplier** with an
**Anti-Corruption Layer** on the receiving end so no model leaks across.

.box {Read more} type:{tip}
