    [Strategic Design → Context Map](../../dev/Developer-Guide/strategic-design/#context-map).
    The per-context models:
    [Identity & Access](../../dev/Developer-Guide/identity-access/) ·
    [Building Management](../../dev/Developer-Guide/building-management/) ·
    [Telemetry Ingestion](../../dev/Developer-Guide/telemetry-ingestion/) ·
    [Telemetry Distribution](../../dev/Developer-Guide/telemetry-distribution/) ·
    [Alerting](../../dev/Developer-Guide/alerting/).

## 2.2 One context, one service

Each context maps cleanly onto a deployable service. Every service owns its persistence, answers
synchronous reads over HTTP, and trades the high-frequency events over a broker.

.var {headers}
   - Service
   - Bounded context
   - Stack
   - Store

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - auth-service
      - Identity & Access
      - Node.js / Express
      - MongoDB
    - - twin-service
      - Building Management
      - Node.js / Express
      - MongoDB
    - - sensor-service
      - Telemetry Ingestion
      - Node.js / Express
      - MongoDB
    - - contracts-service
      - Telemetry Distribution
      - Rust / Axum
      - MongoDB (read state cached in memory)
    - - notification-service
      - Alerting
      - Node.js / Express
      - MongoDB
    - - socket-service
      - Real-time transport
      - Node.js / Socket.IO
      - —
    - - agent-service
      - Knowledge & Assistance
      - Python
      - PostgreSQL

.box {Read more} type:{tip}
    The whole-system picture, the guiding principles and the routing table:
    [Architecture Overview](../../dev/Developer-Guide/overview/#component-landscape).

## 2.3 How the services talk

We use two styles of communication, and we chose between them on purpose:

- **Synchronous, over HTTP** through a single gateway — for the things a user does, and for the few
  service-to-service calls that genuinely need an answer on the spot. Identity rides along in the
  signed token, so no service ever has to phone another just to *authorise* a request.
- **Asynchronous, publish/subscribe over Redis** — for the steady stream of telemetry and alerts,
  where a producer should never be slowed down or blocked by whoever happens to be listening.

The behaviour we most wanted to get right — a real-world reading reaching a browser as it happens —
runs end to end across `sensor-service → contracts-service → socket-service`, while a second path
raises threshold alerts through `notification-service` at the same time.

.box {Read more} type:{tip}
    The two real-time sequence diagrams and the channel list:
    [Communication & Data Flow](../../dev/Developer-Guide/data-flow/#asynchronous-communication).

## 2.4 What a service looks like inside

Zoom into most services and you find the same small, layered app: a strict
**Router → Controller → Service → Model** flow, so anyone hopping between services already knows where
the routing, the logic and the data access live. Three services break that pattern deliberately — the
sensor service resolves a per-metric strategy at request time, the Rust contracts service keeps its
hot state in memory (with its database behind it for durability), and the socket service is a flat
broker-to-WebSocket bridge with no database at all. Authorisation and error handling we pulled out
into shared middleware rather than copy-pasting them into every controller.

.box {Read more} type:{tip}
    The layer responsibilities and the deliberate exceptions:
    [Service Anatomy](../../dev/Developer-Guide/microservices/#the-shared-layered-architecture).

## 2.5 Keeping data consistent

Inside its own walls, each service is **strongly consistent** — it writes through its own database and
that is that. Across services we settle for **eventual consistency**: a service finishes its local
write, emits an event, and the others catch up asynchronously. No transaction ever stretches across
two services. The handful of synchronous cross-service calls (used for provisioning) are best-effort
and retried — never sitting on the hot path.

.box {Read more} type:{tip}
    The database-per-service and stateless-service rules that hold this together:
    [Contributing → Architectural golden rules](../../dev/Developer-Guide/contributing/#architectural-golden-rules).

